ht Sky: An Allegory -- t14 Microsatellites: A Bellwether of Chinese Aerospace Progress? -- t15. Disjecta Membra, the Kármán Line, and the 38th Parallel -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDown to Earth presents the first comprehensive overview of the geopolitical maneuvers, financial investments, technological innovations, and ideological struggles that take place behind the scenes of the satellite industry. Satellite projects that have not received extensive coverage—microsatellites in China, WorldSpace in South Africa, SiriusXM, the failures of USA 193 and Cosmos 954, and Iridium—are explored. This collection takes readers on a voyage through a truly global industry, from the sites where satellites are launched to the corporate clean rooms where they are designed, and along the orbits and paths that satellites traverse. Combining a practical introduction to the mechanics of the satellite industry, a history of how its practices and technologies have evolved, and a sophisticated theoretical analysis of satellite cultures, Down to Earth opens up a new space for global media studies.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Jan 2023) 0aArtificial satellites in telecommunicationvPopular works. 0aArtificial satellitesvPopular works. 0aMass mediavPopular works. 0aTelecommunicationxSocial aspectsvPopular works. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAslinger, Ben, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollins, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCollis, Christy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aErickson, Andrew S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHay, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.l